kultstatus77 wrote:

&gt; I&#39;m quite familiar with the purpose of tearDown(), I just fail to see
&gt; the necessity of it. According to M. Feathers&#39; &quot;Working effectively
&gt; with legacy code&quot; unit tests don&#39;t access databases or communicate via
&gt; a nreal network connection. I do know that his book&#39;s focus is not on
&gt; JUnit, but I do think that he has a point there. So: without a
&gt; database and a network connection, when it is really necessary to free
&gt; up resources with tearDown()? Isn&#39;t garbage collecting enough?

Run this code for a while and tell me what happens.

public class MyTestCase extends TestCase {
     public static Test suite() {
         TestSuite suite = new TestSuite();

         for (int i = 0; i &lt; 1000; i++)
             suite.add(new MyTestCase());
         }

         return suite;
     }

     public void testOops() {
         Connection connection = DriverManager.getConnection(&quot;database&quot;, 
&quot;user&quot;, &quot;password&quot;);
         fail(&quot;Oops&quot;);
         connection.close();
     }
}

Now I admit this example is stupid at first sight, but now imagine 
fail(&quot;Oops&quot;); is replaced by more realistic code that throws an 
exception. Eventually you will run out of connections.

Now you could use finally {}, but imagine if you have three or four such 
tests, each duplicating the finally {} block. I find it reveals much 
more intent to grab the connection in setUp() and close it (if needed) 
in tearDown(). At least tearDown() is guaranteed to execute whether the 
test passes or fails.
